  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Arriving Without Private Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Most provinces have a 3-month waiting period. A single ER visit without coverage can cost $5,000-20,000. An appendectomy? $30,000+. Always have private insurance before you land.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Registering for Provincial Healthcare Immediately</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The waiting period starts when you register, not when you arrive. Register with Service Ontario, ICBC, or your province's health ministry in your first week. Delaying registration extends your waiting period.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Working for a Different Employer</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Closed work permits only allow you to work for the employer on your LMIA. Working for anyone else is illegal and can result in deportation and future inadmissibility. If you want to change jobs, you need a new LMIA and work permit.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Letting the LMIA Expire</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">LMIA is valid for 6 months. You must apply for your work permit within this window. If it expires, your employer must apply for a new LMIA. Don't delay your application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Understanding Provincial Differences</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Healthcare rules vary by province. Manitoba has no waiting period; Quebec requires French documentation; Alberta has different registration. Research your specific province before arriving.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Canada -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Canada</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Canada has universal healthcare, but it's administered provincially. Each province has its own health insurance plan (OHIP, MSP, RAMQ, etc.) with different rules. Work permit holders are generally eligible for provincial coverage after a waiting period.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Canadian Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Family Doctor</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Canadians typically have a family doctor (GP) for routine care. Finding one can take time—many areas have doctor shortages. Walk-in clinics are available for those without a family doctor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialists</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Specialist referrals come through your family doctor. Wait times vary by specialty and urgency—cancer care is fast, but non-urgent orthopedics can take months.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Emergency rooms are available 24/7. For life-threatening emergencies, care is immediate. For non-urgent ER visits, expect long waits. Urgent care clinics handle moderate issues faster.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What Provincial Healthcare Covers</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Doctor visits:</strong> Family doctor and specialists (with referral)</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital care:</strong> Emergency, surgery, inpatient treatment</li>
      <li><strong>Diagnostic tests:</strong> X-rays, MRIs, blood tests (when ordered by doctor)</li>
      <li><strong>Maternity:</strong> Prenatal, delivery, postnatal care</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What You Need Private Insurance For</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Prescription drugs:</strong> Provincial plans have limited drug coverage</li>
      <li><strong>Dental:</strong> Not covered by provincial plans</li>
      <li><strong>Vision:</strong> Eye exams and glasses not covered for working adults</li>
      <li><strong>Physiotherapy:</strong> Limited coverage unless hospitalized</li>
      <li><strong>Mental health:</strong> Psychologists not covered (psychiatrists are)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Employer benefits matter:</strong> Good Canadian employers provide extended health benefits covering prescriptions, dental, and vision. This is a significant part of compensation—factor it into job offers. Benefits often start from day one.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long is the provincial healthcare waiting period?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Most provinces have a 3-month waiting period (Ontario, BC, Alberta, Quebec, Saskatchewan). Manitoba has no waiting period—coverage starts immediately. Check your specific province's rules.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on a work permit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          With a closed work permit (most LMIA-based), you can only work for the employer on your permit. To change employers, the new employer must obtain their own LMIA and you must apply for a new work permit.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 1 year of skilled Canadian work experience, you can apply through Express Entry's Canadian Experience Class (CEC). With good English/French scores and work experience, many applicants receive PR invitations within 6-12 months.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse work in Canada?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouses of work permit holders in skilled occupations (NOC TEER 0, 1, 2, 3) are eligible for an open work permit. They can work for any employer without needing their own LMIA. This is a major benefit of Canadian work permits.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if my work permit expires before PR is approved?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If you've applied for PR and your work permit is expiring, you can apply for a Bridging Open Work Permit (BOWP). This allows you to continue working while your PR application is processed. You need to be eligible for the BOWP when applying.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need travel insurance within Canada?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Once you have provincial healthcare, you're covered across Canada for emergency care. However, some provinces don't cover ambulance costs, and non-emergency care may not be fully covered outside your home province. Many Canadians carry travel insurance for trips.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Canada's work permit system offers one of the clearest pathways from temporary work to permanent residence. The LMIA process takes time, but once you're in Canada with skilled work experience, Express Entry provides a fast track to PR. The universal healthcare system is excellent once you're past the provincial waiting period.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The critical insurance consideration is the 3-month waiting period in most provinces. You must have private coverage before you arrive—Canadian healthcare costs are high without insurance. Budget $250-750 for three months of comprehensive coverage.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For skilled workers seeking a stable, high-quality-of-life destination with genuine permanent residence prospects, Canada remains one of the best options globally. The combination of spouse work rights, pathway to PR, and eventual citizenship makes the initial LMIA hurdle worthwhile.
    </p>

